sql:
SELECT DISTINCT ct.crime_type
FROM crime_trends ct
JOIN crime_pattern_analyses cpa ON ct.crime_trend_id = cpa.crime_trend_id;

SELECT crime_type
FROM crime_trends
WHERE crime_rate = (SELECT MAX(crime_rate) FROM crime_trends);

SELECT AVG(crime_rate) AS average_crime_rate
FROM crime_trends
WHERE crime_type = 'Theft';

SELECT COUNT(*) AS theft_count
FROM crime_trends
WHERE crime_type = 'theft';

SELECT AVG(ct.crime_rate) AS average_crime_rate
FROM crime_trends ct
INNER JOIN crime_pattern_analyses cpa ON ct.crime_trend_id = cpa.crime_trend_id;

external_knowledge:
- This query assumes that crime trends are being analyzed to identify patterns and areas with high crime rates; 
- The average crime rate per area helps in comparing crime rates across different areas; 
- The latest analysis date and notes provide insights into the most recent analysis performed for each crime trend.

External knowledge:

- Top crime trends refer to those with the highest crime rates in their respective areas; 
- The rank of a crime trend is determined by its position in the ordered list of crime rates within its area, with 1 being the highest; 
- Analysis details include the date the analysis was performed and any relevant notes about the analysis.
